					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 11th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment.</support>
								<extent>237 folios<dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
										<height>205</height>
										<width>165</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>160</height>
										<width>105</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>237 folios (+ 3 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 4 at the end). </p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Quires of mostly 10 leaves each, marked with catchwords at the end.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Usage stains.</p>
									<p>Incomplete at the beginning.</p>
									<p>Folio 227 mutilated.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1" ruledLines="25" writtenLines="25">
									<p>Uniform layout.</p>
									<p>Titles in larger square script, coloured in red. Initial words in larger square script.</p>
									<p>Visible pricking and hard-point ruling.</p>
									<p>Hair side and flesh side of folios distinguishable.</p>
									<p>Red edges.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="7">
							<summary>Italian square scripts of the 11th century. </summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole">
								<p>
									<locus from="1r" to="6v"/> and <locus from="39r" to="201v"/> written by the main scribe. Portions: <locus from="7r" to="12r"/>, <locus from="12v" to="13r"/>, <locus from="13v" to="25r"/>, <locus from="25r" to="38v"/>, <locus from="201v" to="205v"/>, <locus from="206r" to="226r"/> written by six different hands, respectively.</p>
							</handNote>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Folios 228-237 are a portion of a different manuscript, forming a single quire with a catchword at the end. Written in an Italian square script of the 13th century. </p>
						</additions>
